\begin{block}{VoIP / IP Video Conferencing}
\begin{itemize}
\item Playout Delay trade-off: Interactivity vs. Voice Quality \\
\item FEC: App. layer redundancy
\end{itemize}
\end{block}

\begin{block}{CCN Strategies}
\begin{itemize}
\item CCN layer redundancy
\item Resolving bursty losses\\ 
$\rightarrow$ Send on different interface\\
\end{itemize}
\end{block}
\end{columns}
\end{frame}

\note[enumerate]{
\scriptsize
\item Real-time communications: VoIP, Video Conferencing, real-time games
\item Each of them share following characteristics: 1) Very delay-sensitive, 2) Loss-tolerant, but only to a certain point, 3) Low throughput requirements.
\item Example: Immersive 3D-Video (mentioned in keynote talk): Delay-sensitive, but high throughput.
\item Playout delay: Making a tradeoff between loss of interactivity and loss of voice quality.\\
Delay too long: Uncomfortable to speak, echos\\
Delay too short: Throwing away late packets (late losses): Degrading voice quality.
\item CCN layer redundancy: Only on lossy hop-to-hop link instead of whole path (more efficient)
\item Bursty losses are a big problem for QoS, because late losses make retransmission nearly impossible
\item $\rightarrow$ Redundancy/Retx on CCN layer to deal with loss bursts.
}



